[On top of the information in the above excerpts, additional ASF-related information from China and Mongolia, including FAO's recommendations regarding other countries of the region, national considerations, interregional collaboration and solidarity, and a summary of FAO's actions so far, is included. There is also a table presenting a list of affected cities in each infected province since 3 Aug 2018, a figure illustrating the number of ASF-reported villages by region and onset month, and a map presenting the 103 outbreaks since the start of the event.

Mongolia submitted its 2nd follow-up report on 29 Jan 2019; it is available, with an interactive map, at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=29337. This referred to the ASF virus circulation in the aimags Selenge and Darkhan-Uul.

OIE's summary of the Mongolian event, as of 27 Jan 2019, is as follows:
Total outbreaks = 10 (submitted)
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Swine / not available / 561 / 561 / 757 / 0

In view of its extensive spread, it was suspected that the actual introduction of the ASF virus into Mongolia could have taken place at an undefined time prior to its detection. In March 2017, the virus was identified in Russia's oblast Irkutsk, adjacent to Mongolia's northern aimag Selenge, which is currently known to be infected (see archive no. 20170328.4929925). - Mod.AS

